tool.title: Discrete Dipole Approximation Code (DDSCAT).
tool.about: Graphical simulation of DDSCAT 7.3, a freely available software package which applies the "discrete dipole approximation" (DDA) to calculate scattering and absorption of electromagnetic waves by an array of polarizable points. The code was developed by Bruce T. Draine and Piotr J. Flatau.

about.label: Shape of Nanosystem
about.description: Select target geometry that will be used to describe the coordinate system attached to the target frame.

about.label: Import from DDAConvert Selection
about.description: Target composed of possibly anisotropic material, defined by list of dipole locations and "compositions" obtained from a file.

about.label: Custom Shape from File
about.description: Target composed of possibly anisotropic material, defined by list of dipole locations and "compositions" obtained from a file.

about.label: Ellipsoid (Diameter Lengths, not Radius)
about.description: Homogeneous, isotropic ellipsoid. "Diameter Lengths" SHPAR1, SHPAR2, SHPAR3 correspond to the x, y, z directions in the target frame respectively. A homogeneous, isotropic sphere is obtained by setting SHPAR1 = SHPAR2 = SHPAR3.

about.label: Anisotropic Ellipsoid (Diameter Lengths, not Radius)
about.description: Homogeneous, anisotropic ellipsoid. "Diameter Lengths" SHPAR1, SHPAR2, SHPAR3 correspond to the x, y, z directions in the target frame respectively. The three composition materials required correspond to the x, y, z elements of the dielectric tensor.

about.label: Concentric Ellipsoids (Diameter Lengths, not Radius)
about.description: Two concentric ellipsoids. SHPAR1, SHPAR2, SHPAR3 specify the diameter lengths along x, y, z axes of the outer ellipsoid; SHPAR4-6 specify the diameter lengths along the x, y, z axes of the inner ellipsoid. The "core" within the inner ellipsoid is composed of isotropic material 1; the "mantle" between inner and outer ellipsoids is composed of isotropic material 2.

about.label: Cylinder
about.description: Homogeneous, isotropic cylinder. Length = SHPAR1, diameter = SHPAR2.

about.label: Cylinder with End-Caps
about.description: Homogeneous, isotropic cylinder with hemispherical end-caps. Cylinder length (not including caps!) = SHPAR1, diameter = SHPAR2. Note that the target length (including end-caps) will be (SHPAR1 + SHPAR2).

about.label: Cylinder with Uniaxial Dielectric Tensor
about.description: Homogeneous cylinder with unixial anisotropic dielectric tensor. Length = SHPAR1, Diameter = SHPAR2.

about.label: Rectangular Solid
about.description: Homogenous, isotropic, rectangular solid. x, y, z lengths = SHPAR1, SHPAR2, SHPAR3.

about.label: Define a Wavelength Window for Light Spectrum to be Observed

about.description: Number of points within the delimited Spectrum.

about.label: Division Seperation Scale Type
about.description: Select scale for spacing the wavelengths.

about.label: Linear
about.description: The wavelengths will be uniformly spaced.

about.label: Inverse
about.description: The wavelengths will be uniformly spaced in 1/lambda.

about.label: Logarithmic
about.description: The wavelengths will be uniformly spaced in log(lambda).

about.label: User supplied
about.description: The wavelengths will be read from the user supplied table, one wavelength per line.

about.label: Wavelength with maximum light extinction intensity is considered.
Nearfield Calculation
about.description: Whether the first DDSCAT calculation should be followed by a second calculation to evaluate electric field throughout a rectangular volume containing the target.

about.label: Define a line and how to read Nearfield parameters along it.
Fractional extension of the calculation volume
Calculate Torque?
about.description: Select whether or not you want radiative torque calculations.

about.label: Solution Method
about.description: Select the iterative method to be used for solving the system of linear equations.

about.label: PBCGST
about.description: Preconditioned Biconjugate Gradient with Stabilization method from the Parallel Iterative Methods package created by R. Dias da Cunha and T. Hopkins.

about.label: PETRKP
about.description: The complex conjugate gradient algorithm of Petravic & Kuo-Petravic, as coded in the Complex Conjugate Gradient package (CCGPACK) created by P.J. Flatau.

about.label: QMRCCG
about.description: The quasi-minimum-residual complex conjugate gradient algorithm, based on f77 code written by P.C. Chaumet and A. Rahmani, converted here to f90 and adapted to single/double precision.

about.label: GPBICG
about.description: Generalized Product-type methods based on Bi-CG Zhang (1997). We use an implementation suggested by Tang et al. (2004), and coded by P.C. Chaumet and A. Rahmani (Chaumet & Rahmani 2009).

about.label: PBCGS2
about.description: BiConjugate Gradient with Stabilization as implemented in the routine ZBCG2 by M.A. Botchev, University of Twente. This is based on the PhD thesis of D.R. Fokkema, and on work by Sleijpen & van der Vorst (1995, 1996).

about.label: DDA Method
about.description: Select the method of solving the DDA problem.

about.label: GKDLDR
about.description: The polarizability is prescribed by the "Lattice Dispersion Relation", with the polarizability found by Gutkowicz-Krusin & Draine(2004).

about.label: LATTDR
about.description: The polarizability is prescribed by the "Lattice Dispersion Relation".

about.label: FLTRCD
about.description: The "filtered coupled dipole" (FCD) method proposed by Piller & Martin (1998).

about.label: Interaction Cutoff Parameter
about.description: Limits certain summations for periodic targets. If the target is not periodic, this value will be ignored.

about.label: Angular Resolution
about.description: Number of angles is proportional to [(3+x)/ETASCA]^2.

about.label: Number of Scattering Planes
about.description: Choose from either using one or two scattering planes during simulation. If your simulation did not run properly, consider changing this value from 1 to 2 or 2 to 1 respectively.

about.label: Object Periodicity
about.description: Defines whether the target object should be repeated infinitely in one or two dimensions.

about.label: Center-of-Object to Center-of-Object Spacing for repeated/periodic systems
Auto-Set minimum spacing between repeated shapes in Y-direction
about.description: Disregards the user-set value and solves for the minimum spacing with no shape overlap.

about.label: Auto-Set minimum spacing between repeated shapes in Z-direction
about.description: Disregards the user-set value and solves for the minimum spacing with no shape overlap.

about.label: Maximum Iterations
about.description: The maximum number of complex-conjugate-gradient iterations.

about.label: Number of minutes to allow for parallel processing
about.description: This value does NOT affect Local DDSCAT simulations. Choose minutes to use for parallel processing, too small a value may result in incomplete simulations. Guessing close to the approximate simulation time may reward faster queue times.

about.label: Execution Type
about.description: Choose whether to run DDSCAT in its local version; or run DDSCAT in parallel through a queue.

about.label: Virtual-Local DDSCAT (12 Hour Limit)
about.description: Run DDSCAT on the local node. Not recommended for long jobs.

about.label: Remote Parallel DDSCAT with wavelength splitting
about.description: Run DDSCAT remotely. Designed for use with Wavelength Window Divisions > 1. For example, a job that requests 15 wavelength divisions will require 15 seperate job submissions. For very large runs this is the best way to get parallel performance. For smaller jobs, wait times in the remote queue may dominate.

about.label: E-mail when the simulation is done?
about.description: Receive a notification when the simulation is complete
